content.description: Sit start on the leftside of the whipping post boulder and finish straight up.
content.location: Left side of the Whipping Post Boulder.

content.description: Start on the big hold in the roof of whipping post with right hand on the undercling-crimp and left hand on the big pinch, paste your feet on the roof and lunge to the hold at the lip and finish whipping post. I thought it felt 6 or 7.
Start on "Baby Whip". Get upside down with foot and hand jams. Instead of topping out "Baby Whip", top out on "Unknown Traverse". I am probably not the FA. If anyone claims it, I will edit post.
content.location: Left of Crack. Same start as Baby Whip.

content.description: Low traverse, sit starting on the left side of the whipping post boulder (start on Word),  move from left to right on a rail. At the end of the rail, move up and top out.
content.location: Left side of the south face of Whipping Post Boulder

content.description: Same start as Left of Crack V1, but traverse right and follow the edge finishing on the same finish as the Whipping Post Problem.
content.location: Same sit start as Left of Crack V1.

content.description: Southwest arête starts low and just left of Word. Use a left crimp sidepull and a small right crimp, and slap up the sloper and to the dish straight up the arête. Mantle over.
content.location: Southwest corner of the Whipping Post Boulder. See the photo for more details.

content.description:
The middle problem on the west face of the Whipping Post boulder. Sit start on the split ledge and figure out a way to move straight up.  

  IMHO, this climb is horrible.
content.location: Middle problem on the west face.

content.description: Sit start with a left hand on the arête and a right hand on the sharp micro side crimp. Move up the blunt arête and good holds up the center of the face. Crux is the first 2 moves in the entire sequence.
content.location: Northwest corner of the Whipping Post Boulder.

content.description: Same sit start as "Left of Crack", but move left through the sloper rail and finish on Word (i.e., top out over Word).
content.location: Same sit start as Left of Crack

content.description: Sit start on the crimps in the middle of the left boulder and climb the sloper rail up and right to the jug. Top out from there on slopers.
content.location: Towards the leftside of the whipping post boulder.

content.description:
Sit start on Word (far left problem on South face) and traverse the entire top, finishing on the prow (far right side of the South face).  

  First crux is the first half of the traverse (in its entirety). The second crux is getting through the slopers and pumpy campus movement.
content.protection: Tons of pads and an attentitive spotter.
content.location: Sit starts on Word (far left side of South face).

content.description: Start with both hands in the lower portion of the crack and a foot in the lower crevice. Shimmy along the crack to the top.
content.location: On the whipping post boulder, the side facing the creek.

content.description: No proper whipping on this one, but at least you'll have a little fun! Start underneath on a good hand jam and kick those legs up! Follow straight up on good holds, and then tell all your friends you climbed the only limestone invert in Austin!
content.location: The crack on the south face, to the right of "Left of Crack" (self explanatory, thank god).

content.description:
Same sit start as Whipping Post Right. Move up through the crimps, but instead of topping directly above, move left into the final crimp of Whipping Post and dump to the finish.  

  Contrived, but then again, most climbing is.
Summary: Same start as the Whipping Post (V5).  Move to the right from the jug pinch to a series of good crimps.

Same start as Whipping Post Right, but instead of topping out directly above, move right through progressively smaller edges and slopers to the dueling pockets (one is a pocket edge and the other is a pocket). Top out directly over the right pocket.
content.protection: Bad landing, multiple pads are a must.

content.description:
Summary: Climb the arete.   

  Details / beta: Starts from one head high crimp and a higher crimp.  Move into a hard pinch on pockets and bad undercling.  Move up to a right crimp and blunt arete pinch.  From here, there are 2 variations to finish.  The right variation seems just as hard as the left, just completely different. The left finish has an awkward bump from a really good undercling and decent feet. The right finish has a heinous lockoff from a sharp crimp and bad feet. 

  Good: Both finish variations can accommodate tall or short climbers. 

  Bad: Both finishes are tough.

Summary: Climb the obvious cave route that starts on the sloping jug pinch, and follow the moves in a circular motion towards the good sloping crimp on the lip, then move up through the edges to the top. 

  Details: Starting on the jug pinch, move left to the sidepull, then right to the sloping crimp.  Big move required to reach and pull to the top. 

  Good: All the holds are solid. 

  Bad: Big move to the top from the lip.
The two boulders that reside directly in front of the Gus Fruh wall, right in front of fern barn.
